snippet.textDisplay:
Ok for the people who are legit curious about the Scar thing, it IS a nickname that he gave to himself.

Scar's birth name was Taka which roughly translates to "Trash" or "Waste". So his parents Ahadi (Promise) and Uru (Diamond) named their sons "King" and "Trash", soooo yeah.

Anyway Scar tried multiple times to kill Mufasa when they were younger, he actually staged a whole coup with a group called the Lion Guard which, as the 2nd eldest prince, he was the leader. When it failed, he ended up killing everyone else in the Guard...

The other notable attempt was at the watering hole. Scar tried to get a water buffalo to fight and kill Mufasa, but Rafiki saved him and the buffalo ended up injuring Scar instead and gave him a nasty drumroll scar. After that, he decided that would be his new name. Bit of an upgrade, really.
snippet.textOriginal:
Ok for the people who are legit curious about the Scar thing, it IS a nickname that he gave to himself.

Scar's birth name was Taka which roughly translates to "Trash" or "Waste". So his parents Ahadi (Promise) and Uru (Diamond) named their sons "King" and "Trash", soooo yeah.

Anyway Scar tried multiple times to kill Mufasa when they were younger, he actually staged a whole coup with a group called the Lion Guard which, as the 2nd eldest prince, he was the leader. When it failed, he ended up killing everyone else in the Guard...

The other notable attempt was at the watering hole. Scar tried to get a water buffalo to fight and kill Mufasa, but Rafiki saved him and the buffalo ended up injuring Scar instead and gave him a nasty *drumroll* scar. After that, he decided that would be his new name. Bit of an upgrade, really.

snippet.textDisplay:
When Jeremy Irons said "Long live the King" his delivery was so hateful, so moving it cancelled the joy of seeing Mufasa climb out of that gorge. It struck a tone that defined that scene and left a resonating dread in the viewer as the the murder unfolded. When Chiwetel Ejiofor repeated the line he sounded like a power rangers villain overacting. I think that is a fair assessment of this remake. I was more moved by a memory of one line from 1994 than this entire film. Mr. Ejiofor is a fine actor in his own rite, this movie is just a shell. Plus, in several instances, Jeremy's (narrator) singing is better than the film score. Hans Zimmer is a fantastic musician, and composer, this film is just that flat.


How about instead of deflating the good ones Disney remakes some of the flops?
